Although our group adopted various roles throughout this project, I was primarily responsible for testing. The most successful prompts were detailed and specified in the file path, component interface, and desired action. Conversely, vague prompts would not produce useful code. The best example of successful prompt engineering was the ninth prompt, which specified the exact route to be protected and where it should be redirected, and the code was accurate on the first attempt. Thus, the more specific the prompt, the better the code.  

The tests we ran were performed using Vitest. Writing reliable tests requires critical thinking and consideration of expected outcomes. Just because the code runs, it does not mean it meets the functional and non-functional requirements. For example, there were instances when the application would pass basic tests but still fail in minor ways, such as not rendering the RSVP count correctly or failing to redirect non-admin users properly. 

These subtle errors occurred only when our tests attempted to emulate user actions, and they demonstrate that spec-driven development is only as effective as the thought process behind it. When we were clear about what we wanted and why, the AI produced what we asked for. When we were unsure, we made assumptions, gambled, and were occasionally incorrect. Saving every prompt in GitHub gave us what almost no codebases have: a written record of intent, not just a written record of the outcome. This discipline of defining what to do before actually doing it is how any piece of software should be built.  

If I were to complete a project like this again, I would emphasize our rotation more, rather than primarily being the tester. Being more involved in the prompting of each section earlier on would likely have improved our spec and subsequent tests. I'd also consider adding more frequent, micro-validations immediately following each prompt, rather than accumulating larger sections to test at the end. This would likely have prevented some of those later errors from appearing sooner.